/issues.apache.org/jira/images/icons/statuses/resolved.png","name":"Resolved","id":"5","statusCategory":{"self":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/statuscategory/3","id":3,"key":"done","colorName":"green","name":"Done"}},"components":[{"self":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/component/12311393","id":"12311393","name":"scripts"}],"timeoriginalestimate":null,"description":"I'm using Hadoop on Ubuntu 6.10.  I ran into:\n\n$ start-all.sh\nstarting namenode, logging to\n/usr/local/hadoop-install/hadoop/bin/../logs/hadoop-jj-namenode-jjinuxland.out\n/usr/local/hadoop-install/hadoop/bin/slaves.sh: 36: Syntax error: Bad\nsubstitution\nstarting jobtracker, logging to\n/usr/local/hadoop-install/hadoop/bin/../logs/hadoop-jj-jobtracker-jjinuxland.out\n/usr/local/hadoop-install/hadoop/bin/slaves.sh: 36: Syntax error: Bad\nsubstitution\n\nUbuntu 6.10 switched away from using bash for the default /bin/sh.\nThe workaround is simple:\n\n(cd /bin && ln -sf bash sh)\n\nNonetheless, it might be nice to update the script so that it works by\ndefault on Ubuntu since it is pretty popular.  I'm guessing that the\nchange would be simple.  The offending line is:\n\nssh $HADOOP_SSH_OPTS $slave $\"${@// /\\\\ }\" \\\n","customfield_10010":null,"timetracking":{},"customfield_12312026":null,"customfield_12312023":null,"customfield_12310320":null,"customfield_12312024":null,"customfield_12312340":null,"attachment":[],"aggregatetimeestimate":null,"customfield_12312341":null,"customfield_12312220":null,"customfield_12312022":null,"customfield_12310921":null,"customfield_12310920":"53832","customfield_12312823":null,"summary":"start-all.sh fails on Ubuntu 6.10","creator":{"self":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=jjinux","name":"jjinux","key":"jjinux","avatarUrls":{"48x48":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?avatarId=10452","24x24":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=small&avatarId=10452","16x16":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=xsmall&avatarId=10452","32x32":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=medium&avatarId=10452"},"displayName":"Shannon -jj Behrens","active":true,"timeZone":"Etc/UTC"},"subtasks":[],"customfield_12310291":null,"reporter":{"self":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=jjinux","name":"jjinux","key":"jjinux","avatarUrls":{"48x48":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?avatarId=10452","24x24":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=small&avatarId=10452","16x16":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=xsmall&avatarId=10452","32x32":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=medium&avatarId=10452"},"displayName":"Shannon -jj Behrens","active":true,"timeZone":"Etc/UTC"},"customfield_12310290":null,"aggregateprogress":{"progress":0,"total":0},"customfield_12311024":null,"environment":"Ubuntu 6.10 (and presumably Debian Etch)","customfield_12313520":null,"customfield_12311020":null,"duedate":null,"customfield_12310250":null,"progress":{"progress":0,"total":0},"comment":{"comments":[{"self":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/issue/12359839/comment/12639358","id":"12639358","author":{"self":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=udanax","name":"udanax","key":"udanax","avatarUrls":{"48x48":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?ownerId=udanax&avatarId=11334","24x24":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=small&ownerId=udanax&avatarId=11334","16x16":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=xsmall&ownerId=udanax&avatarId=11334","32x32":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=medium&ownerId=udanax&avatarId=11334"},"displayName":"Edward J. Yoon","active":true,"timeZone":"Etc/UTC"},"body":"Change the /bin/sh symlink on Ubuntu systems to point to the bash shell instead of the default dash shell.\n\nIt should be closed since it is not a hadoop bug.","updateAuthor":{"self":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=udanax","name":"udanax","key":"udanax","avatarUrls":{"48x48":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?ownerId=udanax&avatarId=11334","24x24":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=small&ownerId=udanax&avatarId=11334","16x16":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=xsmall&ownerId=udanax&avatarId=11334","32x32":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=medium&ownerId=udanax&avatarId=11334"},"displayName":"Edward J. Yoon","active":true,"timeZone":"Etc/UTC"},"created":"2008-10-14T09:25:09.346+0000","updated":"2008-10-14T09:25:09.346+0000"},{"self":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/issue/12359839/comment/12639361","id":"12639361","author":{"self":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=udanax","name":"udanax","key":"udanax","avatarUrls":{"48x48":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?ownerId=udanax&avatarId=11334","24x24":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=small&ownerId=udanax&avatarId=11334","16x16":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=xsmall&ownerId=udanax&avatarId=11334","32x32":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=medium&ownerId=udanax&avatarId=11334"},"displayName":"Edward J. Yoon","active":true,"timeZone":"Etc/UTC"},"body":"I just closed this issue. If it's asked frequently enough, let's add to Frequently Asked Questions.","updateAuthor":{"self":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=udanax","name":"udanax","key":"udanax","avatarUrls":{"48x48":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?ownerId=udanax&avatarId=11334","24x24":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=small&ownerId=udanax&avatarId=11334","16x16":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=xsmall&ownerId=udanax&avatarId=11334","32x32":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=medium&ownerId=udanax&avatarId=11334"},"displayName":"Edward J. Yoon","active":true,"timeZone":"Etc/UTC"},"created":"2008-10-14T09:32:37.784+0000","updated":"2008-10-14T09:32:37.784+0000"},{"self":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/issue/12359839/comment/12639383","id":"12639383","author":{"self":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=steve_l","name":"steve_l","key":"steve_l","avatarUrls":{"48x48":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?avatarId=10452","24x24":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=small&avatarId=10452","16x16":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=xsmall&avatarId=10452","32x32":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=medium&avatarId=10452"},"displayName":"Steve Loughran","active":true,"timeZone":"Etc/UTC"},"body":"So on Ubuntu 8.10 any script that goes\n#!/bin/sh\nat the front is going to break? That's an Ubuntu regression, which could break a lot of things, who end up fielding the support calls\n\n(pause)\nyes, they've noticed: http://brainstorm.ubuntu.com/idea/2225/\n\nbut if you follow through, it's a WONTFIX\nhttps://bugs.launchpad.net/ubuntu/+source/dash/+bug/61463\nhttps://bugs.launchpad.net/ubuntu/+source/dash/+bug/141481\n\n\"all scripts are expected to say #!/bin/bash ; because if you want bash, you had better ask for it explicitly.\"\n\nLooking at the ubuntu discussion, their view is code that assumes that /bin/sh -> bash contains the bug; not Ubuntu, which is only required to link to a POSIX-compliant version of sh, not bash. From that point of view, if the hadoop scripts conatin bash-isms, then, yes, it is the hadoop shell scripts that are at fault. This doesn't mean that the Ubuntu changes are acceptable, only that they are defensible. \n","updateAuthor":{"self":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=steve_l","name":"steve_l","key":"steve_l","avatarUrls":{"48x48":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?avatarId=10452","24x24":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=small&avatarId=10452","16x16":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=xsmall&avatarId=10452","32x32":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=medium&avatarId=10452"},"displayName":"Steve Loughran","active":true,"timeZone":"Etc/UTC"},"created":"2008-10-14T11:20:02.608+0000","updated":"2008-10-14T11:20:02.608+0000"},{"self":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/issue/12359839/comment/12639412","id":"12639412","author":{"self":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=bockelman","name":"bockelman","key":"bockelman","avatarUrls":{"48x48":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?avatarId=10452","24x24":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=small&avatarId=10452","16x16":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=xsmall&avatarId=10452","32x32":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=medium&avatarId=10452"},"displayName":"Brian Bockelman","active":true,"timeZone":"America/Chicago"},"body":"Agreed.\n\nIf we use a command that is not supported by a POSIX-compliant version of sh, and make the assumption that /bin/sh = /bin/bash (which is not true), then we ought to explicitly ask for bash...\n\nLooks like a Hadoop bug to me.  Reopen?","updateAuthor":{"self":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=bockelman","name":"bockelman","key":"bockelman","avatarUrls":{"48x48":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?avatarId=10452","24x24":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=small&avatarId=10452","16x16":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=xsmall&avatarId=10452","32x32":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=medium&avatarId=10452"},"displayName":"Brian Bockelman","active":true,"timeZone":"America/Chicago"},"created":"2008-10-14T13:20:42.385+0000","updated":"2008-10-14T13:20:42.385+0000"},{"self":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/issue/12359839/comment/12639743","id":"12639743","author":{"self":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2